>>> Main Code Structure  
This section provides a detailed functional breakdown of the main Python script used on the Raspberry Pi. It shows how different components—AI 
logic, communication, and camera input—are orchestrated together for real-time tracking and drone control.

1. Global Variables and Constants : Defined constants for camera configuration, object thresholds, and UART setup: 
FRAME_WIDTH = 320 
FRAME_HEIGHT = 240 
CENTER_THRESHOLD = 50 
SERIAL_PORT = "/dev/ttyS0" 
BAUD_RATE = 115200 
• These values define the resolution for inference, object offset range, and communication settings.

2. Initialization (setup() equivalent) : All key modules are initialized at the beginning of the script: 
• Camera Stream Setup: 
cap = cv2.VideoCapture(0) 
cap.set(cv2.CAP_PROP_FRAME_WIDTH, FRAME_WIDTH) 
cap.set(cv2.CAP_PROP_FRAME_HEIGHT, FRAME_HEIGHT) 
• Serial Connection to Flight Controller: 
ser = serial.Serial(SERIAL_PORT, BAUD_RATE, timeout=1) 
• Load TensorFlow Lite Interpreter: 
interpreter = tflite.Interpreter(model_path="model.tflite") 
interpreter.allocate_tensors() 
input_details = interpreter.get_input_details() 
output_details = interpreter.get_output_details()

3. Main Loop (loop() equivalent) : This is the core real-time execution loop: 
• Frame Capture & Preprocessing: 
ret, frame = cap.read() 
frame_resized = cv2.resize(frame, (input_width, input_height)) 
input_data = np.expand_dims(frame_resized / 255.0, 
axis=0).astype(np.float32) 
• AI Model Inference: 
interpreter.set_tensor(input_details[0]['index'], input_data) 
interpreter.invoke() 
output_data = interpreter.get_tensor(output_details[0]['index']) 
• Bounding Box Analysis: 
# Assume a single box for simplification 
x1, y1, x2, y2 = output_data[0][:4] 
cx = (x1 + x2) // 2 
offset = cx - FRAME_WIDTH // 2 
• Movement Command Decision: 
if offset > CENTER_THRESHOLD: 
command = "YAW_RIGHT" 
elif offset < -CENTER_THRESHOLD: 
command = "YAW_LEFT" 
else: 
command = "HOLD" 
• Serial Communication: 
ser.write((command + "\n").encode()) 
• Optional Visual Debug: 
cv2.rectangle(frame, (x1, y1), (x2, y2), (0, 255, 0), 2) 
cv2.imshow("Tracking", frame)

4. Cleanup on Exit :  Releases all resources when script exits: 
cap.release() 
cv2.destroyAllWindows() 
ser.close() 


>>>  This structure ensures the system can loop endlessly, capturing, processing, deciding, and commanding in real time with minimal latency.
